{"id":"5e9c06de774c2610387e4f09","title":"Artist Profile: Lucy Kirk","content":"<p>Who’d ever thought sexy ladies in their undies could belong on your bedroom shelf? Unless you’ve buffed up Barbie, or dig the Bratz (Slutz), then all your dreams have come true.</p><p> All hail <b>Lucy Kirk</b> for creating her new series: <b>Showgirls</b>.  You can take your pick from Poppy, Jess, Tegan or even Meg, who looks especially naughty. For your viewing pleasure, please click <a href=\"https://www.lucy-kirk.co.uk/index.php?/showgirls/ceramics-/\"><strong>HERE</strong></a>.</p>\n<p>All joking aside, I can’t see anyone not having a giggle to Lucys work, and this is what I love about it. I can imagine trying to mould provocative poses on a small scale quite a tricky job, but it’s the bumpy and slightly swished limbs that make them so endearing and entertaining. Not to mention the accompaniment of bored expressions.</p>\n<p>She has also teamed up with fellow Brighton graduate, <b>Millie Popovic</b>, to create<b> Pen on Paper (POP),</b> a partnership established ‘<i>because of our mutual love of lidos, partially dressed swimmers and hay barns’, </i>evident in their Swimmer Notebooks and Tanning T-shirts.</p>\n<p>Showgirls, swimmers, garters, haybails…it think I need to fetch a hot flannel! What I sense is a playfulness at the people who are seemingly ‘on stage’; the places where people are seen in their fleshy egos. It must be a lot of fun putting these characters into everyday contexts, and this might just be what fuels the fire (literally, she’s probably got a kiln) in the world of Lucy Kirk.</p>\n\n\t\t<style type=\"text/css\">\n\t\t\t#gallery-2 {\n\t\t\t\tmargin: auto;\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t#gallery-2 .gallery-item {\n\t\t\t\tfloat: left;\n\t\t\t\tmargin-top: 10px;\n\t\t\t\ttext-align: center;\n\t\t\t\twidth: 33%;\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t#gallery-2 img {\n\t\t\t\tborder: 2px solid #cfcfcf;\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t#gallery-2 .gallery-caption {\n\t\t\t\tmargin-left: 0;\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t/* see gallery